[REASON:planning]   <orientation>The part is mounted vertically to a wall or monitor via the VESA plate. The tray extends forward and downward at a 30-degree angle. The bottom of the support struts is the lowest point (Z=10mm), but the part does not rest on a table; it is wall-mounted.</orientation>
[REASON:planning]   <contact_surfaces>The VESA plate back face (Y=-12.5) contacts the wall/monitor mount. The tray top surface (tilted) contacts the laptop bottom. The support struts contact the tray underside.</contact_surfaces>
[REASON:planning]   <applied_forces>Laptop weight (~1.5kg) acts downwards and slightly forward due to the tilt. The supports resist the downward force. The VESA plate resists the torque generated by the cantilevered laptop.</applied_forces>
[REASON:planning]   <containment_strategy>Gravity holds the laptop on the tray. The back edge of the tray (supported by struts) prevents the laptop from sliding backward. The front edge is open, but the 30-degree tilt is shallow enough that a laptop won't slide forward easily.</containment_strategy>
